    "body": "@karalabe - did you get a chance to look at this? After a few experiments, I am sure that this is related to the chain not being initialized with `eip158Block` (the chains we have are fairly new, so they block number hasn't crossed the hard fork limit specified in the code ~2.5 million). When I start a chain with `eip158Block: n`, the chain continues to work without errors after migrating to `1.8.14`. In lieu of changing genesis block and re-creating chain, I attempted to migrate to a forked version of `1.8.14` to force the hard fork to `EIP158` with the following patch (this would force newer blocks produced after migration to be mined with EIP158 behavior):\r\n\r\n```\r\n+++ b/params/config.go\r\n@@ -40,7 +40,7 @@ var (\r\n                EIP150Block:         big.NewInt(2463000),\r\n                EIP150Hash:          common.HexToHash(\"0x2086799aeebeae135c246c65021c82b4e15a2c451340993aacfd2751886514f0\"),\r\n                EIP155Block:         big.NewInt(2675000),\r\n-               EIP158Block:         big.NewInt(2675000),\r\n+               EIP158Block:         big.NewInt(30),\r\n                ByzantiumBlock:      big.NewInt(4370000),\r\n                ConstantinopleBlock: nil,\r\n                Ethash:              new(EthashConfig),\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe nodes *seem* to work ok but I wanted to check if the above tweak would cause issues for blocks which are in the range [30, m] where `m` is the actual block number which is mined with `EIP158` setting. Let me know your thoughts.",
